{"title_page": "Stroopwafel", "text_new": "{{short description|Thin waffle made with caramel syrup filling}}\n{{expand Dutch|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name            = ''Stroopwafel''\n| image           = Stroopwafels 01.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| caption         = A plate of ''stroopwafels''\n| alternate_name  = Syrup waffle, [[treacle]] waffle, caramel cookie waffle<ref name=gouda-or>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gouda-original.com/|title=Gouda Stroopwafels (Syrup Waffles & Cookies)|website=Gouda Original}}</ref>\n| country         = [[Netherlands]]\n| region          = [[Gouda, South Holland]]\n| creator         = Gerard Kamphuisen<ref name=gouda-or/>\n| course          = \n| type            = [[Waffle]]\n| served          = \n| main_ingredient = Batter: [[flour]], [[butter]], [[brown sugar]], [[Baker's yeast|yeast]], [[milk]], [[Egg (food)|eggs]]<br />Filling: syrup, brown sugar, butter, [[cinnamon]]\n| variations      = \n| calories        = \n| other           = \n}}\n\nA '''''stroopwafel''''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8stro\u02d0p\u02cc\u028ba\u02d0f\u0259l|-|Nl-stroopwafels2.ogg}}; literally \"'''syrup waffle'''\") is a [[wafer]] cookie made from two thin layers of baked dough joined by a [[caramel]] filling.<ref name=\"gouda\">[http://www.gouda-original.com/Webwinkel-Category-141347/Gouda-Stroopwafels-(Syrup-Waffles-&-Cookies).html Stroopwafels. Een traditionele Goudse lekkernij] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104223749/http://www.gouda-online.nl/informatieid-11.html |date=4 January 2008 }} [http://www.gouda-online.nl/ Gouda-Online.nl]. Retrieved on 2 January 2008. {{in lang|nl}}</ref><ref>[http://www.vandale.nl/opzoeken/woordenboek/?zoekwoord=stroopwafel Stroopwafel]. [http://www.vandale.nl/ Van Dale Taalweb]. Retrieved on 2 January 2008. {{in lang|nl}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218235414/http://www.vandale.nl/opzoeken/woordenboek/?zoekwoord=stroopwafel |date=18 February 2012 }}</ref> First made in the Dutch city of [[Gouda, South Holland|Gouda]], stroopwafels are popular throughout the [[Netherlands]] and the former [[Dutch Empire]]{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} and are well-known [[Dutch cuisine|Dutch dishes]].\n\n== Description ==\nA stroopwafel's wafer layers are made from a stiff dough of [[flour]], [[butter]], [[brown sugar]], [[Baker's yeast|yeast]], [[milk]], and [[Egg (food)|eggs]] that has been pressed in a hot [[waffle iron]] until crisped.{{efn|Historically waffles had a diameter of about {{convert|10|cm}}, but they are now available in sizes varying between {{convert|5|and|25|cm}}.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}}} While still warm, the waffles have their edges removed with a [[cookie cutter]], which allows the remaining disc to be easily separated into top and bottom wafers. A caramel filling made from [[syrup]], brown sugar, butter, and cinnamon\u2014also warm\u2014is spread between the wafers before the waffle is reassembled. The caramel sets as it cools, thereby binding the waffle halves together.<ref name=\"gouda\"/>\n\n==History==\nAccording to Dutch culinary folklore, stroopwafels were allegedly first made in [[Gouda, South Holland|Gouda]] either during the late 18th century<ref name=\"waffleshop\">[http://www.stroopwafelshop.com/history.html History & recipe] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213123243/http://www.stroopwafelshop.com/history.html |date=13 December 2007 }}. [http://www.stroopwafelshop.com/ Stroopwafelshop.com]. Retrieved on 3 January 2007.</ref> or the early 19th century<ref name=\"gouda\"/> by bakers repurposing scraps and crumbs by sweetening them with syrup. One story ascribes the invention of the stroopwafel to the baker Gerard Kamphuisen, which would date the first stroopwafels from somewhere between 1810, the year he opened his bakery, and 1840, the year of the oldest known recipe for syrup waffles.<ref name=\"gouda\"/> Stroopwafels were not found outside Gouda until 1870, by which point the city was home to around 100 syrup-waffle bakers.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}.\n\nAs the Netherlands lacks a culinary tradition of waffle making, it is more likely that the Dutch stroopwafel was inspired by if not copied from recipes already circulating in Belgium or [[Flanders]]. Belgium, including the adjacent [[French Flanders]], does have a centuries old tradition of making a huge variety of [[waffles]], such as the \"Brussels waffles\" (aka \"Belgian waffles\" in North America), \"Li\u00e8ge waffles\", \"Gaufres \u00e0 la Flamande\" (aka \"Flemish waffles\") and \"Galettes campinoises\". A version of thin wafer waffles with a sugar filling is  widely known in northern France, viz. in the regional capital Lille (of French Flanders). This local waffle is known as the \"[https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaufre_fourr%C3%A9e_lilloise gaufre fourr\u00e9e lilloise]\", which consists of two thin wafer waffles filled with [[Cane sugar|cassonade]] sugar and vanilla. A recipe for such a waffle with vanilla filling first appeared in 1849, in the workshop of the renowned patisserie, [https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maison_M%C3%A9ert Maison M\u00e9ert], from Lille. Waffles with a filling date back to the Middle Ages, as the famous guidebook for married women, ''[[Le M\u00e9nagier de Paris]]'', compiled in 1393, already includes recipes of waffles with a cheese filling.\n\nAfter 1870 stroopwafels began to appear in other cites, and in the 20th century, factory-made stroopwafels were introduced. By 1960, there were 17 factories in Gouda alone, of which four are still open.<ref name=\"gouda\"/> Today, stroopwafels are sold at markets, by street vendors, and in supermarkets, and since 2016 [[United Airlines]] has been serving stroopwafels as a breakfast snack on its domestic flights.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lazare|first1=Lewis|title=What's Stroopwafel? United Airlines embraces Dutch treat along with fast-growing list of U.S. retailers|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/chicago/news/2016/02/25/whats-stroopwafel-united-airlines-embraces-dutch.html|website=www.bizjournals.com}}</ref>{{efn|Stroopwafels were temporarily replaced with a [[wafer]] in mid 2018,<ref>[https://www.foodandwine.com/news/united-airlines-stroopwafels United Airlines Stopped Serving Stroopwafels and People Are Pissed], ''Food & Wine''</ref> but were brought back in January 2019.<ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-biz-united-airlines-stroopwafels-20190103-story.html United Airlines bringing back stroopwafels], ''Chicago Tribune''</ref><ref>[https://www.thrillist.com/travel/nation/united-airlines-stroopwafels-return-2019 United Is Finally Bringing Back Its Most Beloved In-Flight Snack], ''Thrillist''</ref>}}\n\n== Variants ==\nCookies similar to the stroopwafel may be found in parts of the Netherlands. Wafers with honey instead of syrup are sold as ''honingwafels'', and cookies with a caramel syrup are sold as ''stroopkoeken''. Crumbs of stroopwafels (trimmings from manufacturing) are also sold in candy cones.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n{{-}}\n\n==Gallery==\n{{gallery\n|align=center |lines=3\n|Image:Stroopwafelijzer.jpg|A ball of dough is placed on a waffle iron to make the waffle for a ''stroopwafel''\n|Image:Stroopwafel syrup gouda.jpg|A pot of steaming hot syrup is used to fill the ''stroopwafels''\n|Image:Sr meetup-dec 06-00004.jpg|A packet of store-bought ''stroopwafels''\n|Image:Stroopwafel00.jpg|''Stroopwafels'' on a saucer\n| File:How to eat a stroopwafel (8557345379).jpg|A ''stroopwafel'' is placed over a hot drink such as [[coffee]] or [[tea]] to warm the cookie up and soften the syrup\n|Image:Stroopkoeken.jpg|''Stroopkoeken'' or \"syrup cookies\"\n}}\n\n==Popular culture==\nIn a [[The Great British Bake Off (series 8)#Episode 4: Caramel|September 2017 episode]] of the ''Great British Bake Off'', the contestants had to make ''stroopwafels'', but most failed in what some called the worst technical challenge in the show's history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-09-19/was-this-the-most-disastrous-bake-off-technical-challenge-ever/|title=Was this the most disastrous Bake Off Technical Challenge ever?|website=Radio Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Wafer#Freska|Freska]] \u2013 an Egyptian wafer with honey syrup filling\n* {{annotated link|IJzerkoekje}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Do NOT add commercial information about stroopwafel manufacturers/sellers. This is called linkspam and is considered vandalism. -->\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* [http://www.schepsbakeries.com/video.php How stroopwafels are made.] (video), schepsbakeries.com\n* [http://www.dianasdesserts.com/index.cfm/fuseaction/recipes.recipeListing/filter/dianas/recipeID/694/Recipe.cfm Dutch Stroopwafels] (recipe), dianasdesserts.com\n* [[meta:Association of Stroopwafel Addicts|Association of Stroopwafel Addicts]] at [[Meta-Wiki]]\n\n{{Waffles}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1784 introductions]]\n[[Category:Cookies]]\n[[Category:Dutch confectionery]]\n[[Category:Gouda, South Holland]]\n[[Category:Waffles]]\n[[Category:Dutch cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Thin waffle made with caramel syrup filling}}\n{{expand Dutch|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name            = ''Stroopwafel''\n| image           = Stroopwafels 01.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| caption         = A plate of ''stroopwafels''\n| alternate_name  = Syrup waffle, [[treacle]] waffle, caramel cookie waffle<ref name=gouda-or>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gouda-original.com/|title=Gouda Stroopwafels (Syrup Waffles & Cookies)|website=Gouda Original}}</ref>\n| country         = [[Netherlands]]\n| region          = [[Gouda, South Holland]]\n| creator         = Gerard Kamphuisen<ref name=gouda-or/>\n| course          = \n| type            = [[Waffle]]\n| serv